1. Software

1.1 Download linux-gpib packate and create the new driver subdirectory:

# mkdir linux-gpib-4.1.0/drivers/gpib/gpib_bitbang

1.2 Copy the driver there:

# cp gpib_bitbang.c linux-gpib-4.1.0/drivers/gpib/gpib_bitbang

1.3 Create a Makefile in the gpib_bitbang directory that has the following line:
obj-m += gpib_bitbang.o

1.4 Add the following line to the end of linux-gpib-4.1/drivers/gpib/Makefile :
obj-y += gpib_bitbang/

1.5 Configure and compile as usual:

# ./configure; make; make install)

To load the driver in:

# modprobe gpib_bitbang

2. Hardware

You need to create a cable that connects the rpi3 GPIO header (40 pin connector)
to female GPIB connector as follows:

GPIB pin #	GPIB signal	header pin #
1		D01		Pin 38 (GPIO 20)
2		D02		Pin 37 (GPIO 26)
3		D03		Pin 36 (GPIO 16)
4		D04		Pin 35 (GPIO 19)
13		D05		Pin 33 (GPIO 13)
14		D06		Pin 32 (GPIO 12)
15		D07		Pin 31 (GPIO 6)
16		D08		Pin 29 (GPIO 5)
5		EOI		Pin 21 (GPIO 9)
7		NRFD		Pin 18 (GPIO 24)
9		IFC		Pin 15 (GPIO 22)
11		ATN		Pin 22 (GPIO 25)
17		REN		Pin 13 (GPIO 27)
6		DAV		Pin 19 (GPIO 10)
8		NDAC		Pin 16 (GPIO 23)
10		SRQ		Pin 23 (GPIO 11)

GND(12,18-23,24)   (12 = Shield, 24 = Logic GND)
				At pins 6, 9, 14, 20, 25, 30, 34, 39
OPTIONAL:

		PE		Pin 26 (GPIO 7)	High for write, low for read
		DC		Pin 24 (GPIO 8)	Low for write, high for read
		TE		Pin 12 (GPIO 18)High for write, low for read
		ACT_LED		Pin 7 (GPIO 4)	Activity LED

Connecting LED to Activity: Use 330 Ohm resistor. 
		Connect Anode to + (Pin 7 on the Pi) and Cathode to - 
		(e.g., 6, 9, 14, ...).
Connecting LED to Read: Use 330 Ohm resistor.
		Connect Anode to + (Pin 26 on the Pi) and Cathode to -
		(e.g., 6, 9, 14, ...).
Connecting LED to Write: Use 330 Ohm resistor. 
		Connect Anode to + (Pin 24 on the Pi) and Cathode to - 
		(e.g., 6, 9, 14, ...).
